VERDICT: not-confirmed
REASON: The report's factual claim about the Verus ensures clause is accurate — `validate_decide` (src/userspace.rs:776-779) does not ensure US7, so Verus alone would accept an inverted init branch. However, the report's oracle claim "No Kani harness asserts US7 on validate_decide" is false. ffi/src/lib.rs:7558-7582 contain two Kani proofs, `userspace_validate_uninit_must_be_init` (asserts `d.ret == EINVAL` when `flags & K_OBJ_FLAG_INITIALIZED == 0`, `has_access=1`, `init_check=OBJ_INIT_TRUE`) and `userspace_validate_init_must_not_be_init` (asserts `d.ret == EADDRINUSE` when initialized, `init_check=OBJ_INIT_FALSE`). Both exercise `gale_k_object_validate_decide`, which calls `validate_decide`. The PoC inversion (flipping `!is_initialized` on line 789) makes `userspace_validate_uninit_must_be_init` fail: the inverted body returns `Ok(())` → `ret=OK`, but the harness asserts `ret==EINVAL`. Kani runs in `.github/workflows/formal-verification.yml` with `--all-features` (gating the userspace feature). The differential test is indeed circular as described, but the verification suite as a whole catches the drift via the independent Kani oracle. Secondary blocker: there is no `safety/stpa/ucas.yaml` in the repo — `artifacts/stpa.yaml` explicitly states UCAs are "out of scope for this initial artifact", so no UCA mapping is possible even if confirmed. Not a kernel bug, not a verification escape; a documentation/contract-strengthening suggestion at most.
